04458nam a22005655i 9780226479651DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2018    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802264796517 a10.7208/97802264796512doi  a(DE-B1597)521352  a(OCoLC)1050321264  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aHB3722b.G673 2019 7aBUS0000002bisacsh04a338.54209732231 aGorton, Gary B., eauthor.10aFighting Financial Crises :bLearning from the Past /cEllis W. Tallman, Gary B. Gorton. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b14 line drawings, 12 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Fighting Financial Crises: Learning from the Past -- t2. The New York Clearing House Association -- t3. The Start of a Panic -- t4. What the New York Clearing House Did during National Banking Era Panics -- t5. Information Production and Suppression and Emergency Liquidity -- t6. "Too Big to Fail" before the Fed -- t7. Certified Checks and the Currency Premium -- t8. The Change in Depositors' Beliefs during Suspension -- t9. Aftermath -- t10. What Ends a Financial Crisis? Historical Reminders -- t11. Modern Crises: Perspectives from History -- t12. Guiding Principles for Fighting Crises -- tAppendixes -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIf you've got some money in the bank, chances are you've never seriously worried about not being able to withdraw it. But there was a time in the United States, an era that ended just over a hundred years ago, in which bank customers had to pay close attention to whether the banking system would remain solvent, knowing they might have to rush to retrieve their savings before the bank collapsed. During the National Banking Era (1863-1913), before the establishment of the Federal Reserve, widespread banking panics were indeed rather common. Yet these pre-Fed banking panics, as Gary B. Gorton and Ellis W. Tallman show, bear striking similarities to our recent financial crisis. In both cases, something happened to make depositors-whether individual customers or corporate investors-"act differently" and find reason to question the value of their bank debt. Fighting Financial Crises thus turns to the past for a fuller understanding of our uncertain present, investigating how panics during the National Banking Era played out and how they were eventually quelled and prevented. Gorton and Tallman open with a survey of the period's "information environment," tracing the development of national bank notes, checks, and clearing houses to show how the key to keeping order was to disseminate information very carefully. Identifying the most effective responses based on the framework of the National Banking Era, they then consider the Fed's and the SEC's reactions to the recent crisis, building an informative new perspective on how the modern economy works.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aClearinghouses (Banking)zNew York (State)zNew York. 0aFinancial criseszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aFinancial crises. 4abanking panics. 4afinancial crises. 4asecrecy. 4asuppression of information. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh1 aTallman, Ellis W., eauthor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226479651423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226479651.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles